VALUES
(44, 13, 31, 41, 16, 12, 14, 'his witnesses unto the people', 'Witnesses of the Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of witnesses who saw Jesus after his resurrection. Acts 13:31 mentions those who were witnesses, while Mark 16:14 highlights the disbelief of the eleven regarding those witnesses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 31, 42, 24, 36, 42, 'witnesses unto the people', 'Witnesses of the Resurrected Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of witnessing the resurrected Jesus. In Acts, the witnesses from Galilee to Jerusalem affirm the reality of Jesus'' resurrection, while in Luke, the disciples encounter the risen Jesus directly, reinforcing their role as witnesses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 45, 4, 13, 13, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises to Abraham', 'This connection highlights the theme of promises made to Abraham and his descendants. Both passages emphasize the significance of faith in relation to these promises.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 44, 26, 6, 6, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises to Fathers', 'Both passages emphasize the ''promise made unto the fathers,'' linking the hope of the promise to the message of salvation. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s promises throughout biblical history.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 26, 34, 23, 23, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Promise of Shepherd Leadership', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts, which relates to God''s commitment to provide a shepherd, as seen in Ezekiel. Both passages emphasize the theme of divine guidance through a leader, specifically referencing David as a shepherd figure.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 24, 23, 5, 5, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises and Kingship', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts 13:32, which is fulfilled in the righteous Branch mentioned in Jeremiah 23:5. Both passages emphasize the theme of a divinely appointed leader who will bring justice and prosperity.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 33, 5, 2, 2, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Connection of Promises and Rulership', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts 13:32, which is fulfilled through the ruler mentioned in Micah 5:2. Both passages emphasize the significance of a leader arising from Bethlehem, linking the Old Testament prophecy to the New Testament declaration.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 38, 6, 12, 12, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Promise of the Branch', 'This connection highlights the promise made to the fathers in Acts, which relates to the prophetic declaration of ''the man whose name is The BRANCH'' in Zechariah. Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of God''s promises through a significant figure who will build the temple.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 32, 44, 13, 38, 38, 'the promise which was made unto the fathers', 'Promise and Forgiveness Connection', 'This connection highlights the continuity between the promise made to the fathers and the forgiveness of sins offered through Jesus. Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of God''s promise in the message of salvation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 33, 19, 2, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Sonship and Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine sonship as both passages declare, ''Thou art my Son; this day have I begotten thee.'' Acts 13:33 explicitly references Psalms 2:7, linking the resurrection of Jesus to the affirmation of His identity as God''s Son.', 'quotation', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 33, 58, 5, 5, 5, 'Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee', 'Connection of Sonship in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the declaration of Jesus as God''s Son. The phrase ''Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee'' appears in both contexts, linking Jesus'' identity and role.', 'quotation', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 33, 58, 1, 5, 6, 'Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee', 'Connection of Sonship in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' divine sonship. Both passages reference the phrase, ''Thou art my Son, this day have I begotten thee,'' emphasizing Jesus'' unique relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 23, 55, 3, 3, 'the sure mercies of David', 'Connection of Sure Mercies', 'Both passages emphasize the ''sure mercies of David,'' linking God''s promises to His covenant with David. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s faithfulness from the Old Testament to the New Testament.', 'keyword', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 19, 89, 2, 4, 'sure mercies of David', 'Mercies of David Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s covenant with David, as seen in both passages. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' which aligns with Psalms 89:2-4''s emphasis on God''s faithfulness and establishment of David''s throne.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 45, 6, 9, 9, 'raised him up from the dead', 'Resurrection and Eternal Life', 'Both passages emphasize the resurrection of Christ and its implications for death. Acts 13:34 states that Christ was raised from the dead and will not return to corruption, while Romans 6:9 affirms that death has no more dominion over Him.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 10, 7, 14, 16, 'sure mercies of David', 'Connection of God''s Promises', 'Both passages emphasize God''s enduring mercy and the establishment of a kingdom. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' which relates to the promise of an everlasting throne in 2 Samuel 7:14-16.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 19, 89, 19, 37, 'sure mercies of David', 'Connection of David''s Promises', 'Both passages emphasize God''s covenant with David and the assurance of his enduring lineage. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' which aligns with Psalms 89''s promise of David''s throne lasting forever.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 24, 33, 15, 17, 'the sure mercies of David', 'Connection of Righteousness and David', 'This connection highlights the promise of a righteous leader from David''s lineage, as seen in both passages. Acts 13:34 refers to the ''sure mercies of David,'' while Jeremiah 33:15-17 speaks of the ''Branch of righteousness'' that will arise from David.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 34, 24, 33, 26, 26, 'sure mercies of David', 'Connection of Mercy and David', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mercy associated with David. Acts 13:34 references the ''sure mercies of David,'' while Jeremiah 33:26 speaks of having mercy on the seed of Jacob and David.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 19, 16, 10, 10, 'thine Holy One to see corruption', 'Connection of Holy One and Corruption', 'Both passages emphasize that God''s Holy One will not experience corruption. This connection highlights the assurance of preservation from death and decay.', 'quotation', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 44, 2, 27, 31, 'thine Holy One to see corruption', 'Connection of Resurrection Prophecy', 'Both passages emphasize that God''s Holy One will not see corruption, highlighting the prophetic nature of David''s words regarding the resurrection of Christ. This connection illustrates the fulfillment of prophecy as seen in the New Testament.', 'prophecy', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 19, 49, 9, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Corruption and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of not seeing corruption, suggesting a theme of eternal life or preservation from decay. This connection highlights the significance of the Holy One''s enduring existence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 42, 2, 26, 26, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of not seeing death or corruption. Acts 13:35 speaks of the Holy One not seeing corruption, while Luke 2:26 reveals a promise of not seeing death before witnessing the Lord''s Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 43, 3, 36, 36, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption', 'Connection of Life and Corruption', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the Holy One not seeing corruption and the promise of everlasting life for believers. Both passages emphasize the significance of faith in relation to life and death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 43, 8, 51, 51, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.', 'Connection of Life and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of preservation from death. Acts 13:35 speaks of not seeing corruption, while John 8:51 emphasizes never seeing death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 35, 44, 13, 36, 37, 'Thou shalt not suffer thine Holy One to see corruption.', 'Resurrection and Corruption', 'This connection highlights the contrast between David, who ''saw corruption,'' and Jesus, ''whom God raised again, saw no corruption.'' Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection and the preservation of the Holy One from decay.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 44, 2, 29, 29, 'David, after he had served his own generation', 'David''s Death and Burial', 'Both passages emphasize David''s death and burial, highlighting his mortality. Acts 13:36 mentions David falling asleep, while Acts 2:29 states he is dead and buried.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 10, 7, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection Between David''s Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of David''s death and legacy. Both passages mention David ''sleeping with his fathers,'' indicating a transition to the next generation and the continuation of his lineage.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 11, 2, 10, 10, 'fell on sleep', 'David''s Death and Burial', 'Both passages emphasize David''s death and burial. The phrase ''slept with his fathers'' in 1 Kings parallels the idea of David ''fell on sleep'' in Acts, highlighting the finality of his life.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 44, 13, 22, 22, NULL, 'David''s Fulfillment of God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize David''s role in fulfilling God''s will. Acts 13:22 highlights God''s testimony about David, while Acts 13:36 notes David''s service to his generation by God''s will.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 13, 18, 14, 14, 'served his own generation by the will of God', 'David''s Leadership and Legacy', 'Both passages emphasize David''s role in serving his generation and executing justice. Acts highlights his service by the will of God, while Chronicles reflects his reign and judgment over Israel.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 1, 3, 19, 19, 'saw corruption', 'Connection of Mortality and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the inevitability of death. Acts 13:36 mentions David''s death and corruption, while Genesis 3:19 speaks of returning to dust, highlighting the human condition of mortality.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 36, 13, 13, 2, 4, 'served his own generation by the will of God', 'David''s Leadership and Service', 'This connection highlights David''s role in serving his generation and leading Israel to seek the ark of God. Both passages emphasize David''s commitment to fulfilling God''s will among his people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 37, 44, 13, 30, 30, 'God raised again', 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize God''s action in raising Jesus from the dead. Acts 13:30 states, ''But God raised him from the dead,'' while Acts 13:37 highlights that he ''saw no corruption'' after this resurrection.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 37, 44, 2, 24, 24, 'saw no corruption', 'Resurrection and Corruption', 'Both passages emphasize God''s action in raising Jesus from the dead. Acts 13:37 states that Jesus ''saw no corruption,'' while Acts 2:24 highlights that death could not hold Him, indicating His victory over death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 42, 24, 47, 47, 'forgiveness of sins', 'Forgiveness and Remission of Sins', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forgiveness and the preaching of remission of sins. Acts 13:38 speaks of forgiveness through Jesus, while Luke 24:47 mentions remission of sins to be preached in His name.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 47, 5, 18, 21, 'forgiveness of sins', 'Forgiveness and Reconciliation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of reconciliation and forgiveness through Jesus Christ. Acts 13:38 speaks of the ''forgiveness of sins,'' while 2 Corinthians 5:18-21 discusses God reconciling the world to Himself, not imputing trespasses. This connection highlights the transformative power of Christ''s sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 62, 2, 12, 12, 'forgiveness of sins', 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forgiveness of sins. Acts 13:38 states that forgiveness is preached through Jesus, while 1 John 2:12 affirms that sins are forgiven for His name''s sake.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 44, 5, 31, 31, 'forgiveness of sins', 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forgiveness of sins through Jesus. Acts 13:38 speaks of forgiveness being preached, while Acts 5:31 mentions forgiveness as a gift from God through Jesus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 51, 1, 14, 14, 'forgiveness of sins', 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the forgiveness of sins as a central theme. Acts 13:38 presents forgiveness through Jesus, while Colossians 1:14 highlights it through His blood.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 44, 2, 38, 38, NULL, 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forgiveness of sins. Acts 13:38 speaks of forgiveness through Jesus, while Acts 2:38 mentions remission of sins through repentance and baptism.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 38, 49, 1, 7, 7, 'forgiveness of sins', 'Forgiveness of Sins Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forgiveness of sins through Christ. Acts 13:38 presents the preaching of forgiveness, while Ephesians 1:7 highlights redemption and forgiveness through his blood.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 45, 10, 4, 4, 'justified from all things', 'Justification and the Law', 'Both passages emphasize justification through faith rather than the law. Acts 13:39 states believers are justified from things the law cannot justify, while Romans 10:4 declares Christ as the end of the law for righteousness.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 48, 2, 16, 16, NULL, 'Justification by Faith', 'Both passages emphasize that justification comes through faith rather than the law. Acts 13:39 states believers are justified from all things, while Galatians 2:16 clarifies that no one is justified by the works of the law.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 45, 8, 3, 3, 'justified from all things', 'Justification and the Law', 'This connection highlights the inability of the law to justify believers, as noted in both passages. Acts 13:39 states that believers are justified from all things, while Romans 8:3 emphasizes what the law could not do due to its weakness.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 58, 7, 19, 19, 'justified from all things', 'Justification and Perfection in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of justification through faith in Christ as opposed to the law, which is seen as imperfect. Both passages emphasize that the law cannot achieve perfection or justification, pointing to a better hope found in Christ.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 43, 1, 17, 17, 'justified from all things', 'Justification and Grace Contrast', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the law given by Moses and the grace that comes through Jesus Christ. Both passages emphasize that justification cannot be achieved through the law, but rather through faith in Christ.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 48, 3, 21, 25, 'justified from all things', 'Justification by Faith', 'Both passages emphasize justification through faith rather than the law. Acts 13:39 states believers are justified from all things, while Galatians 3:24 highlights the law as a schoolmaster leading to justification by faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 39, 58, 10, 11, 11, 'justified from all things', 'Justification and Sacrifice Connection', 'This connection highlights the contrast between justification through faith and the ineffectiveness of the law and sacrifices. Acts 13:39 emphasizes justification from all things, while Hebrews 10:11 notes that sacrifices can never take away sins.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 39, 4, 1, 1, 'which is spoken of in the prophets', 'Judgment and Warning Connection', 'This connection highlights a warning of impending judgment. Both passages emphasize the consequences for the proud and wicked, with Acts referencing prophetic warnings and Malachi describing the destructive day of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 35, 1, 5, 5, 'that come upon you', 'Warning of Unbelief', 'This connection highlights a warning against disbelief in God''s work. Both passages emphasize the unexpected nature of God''s actions, urging the audience to be aware of the consequences of not believing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 39, 3, 2, 2, 'which is spoken of in the prophets', 'Judgment and Refinement Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment and purification. Acts 13:40 warns of consequences foretold by the prophets, while Malachi 3:2 speaks of the refining process associated with the coming of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 58, 3, 12, 12, NULL, 'Warning Against Unbelief', 'This connection highlights the theme of caution against unbelief. Both passages emphasize the need to be vigilant to avoid departing from faith in God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 58, 12, 25, 25, 'that come upon you, which is spoken of in the prophets', 'Warning Against Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of warning against rejecting God''s message. Both passages emphasize the consequences of refusing to heed divine communication, whether from prophets or from heaven.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 40, 3, 9, 12, 'that come upon you, which is spoken of in the prophets', 'Warning of Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of impending judgment and the call for repentance. Both passages emphasize the consequences of failing to produce good fruit and the urgency of heeding prophetic warnings.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 40, 23, 29, 14, 14, 'which is spoken of in the prophets', 'Connection of Wisdom and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention leading to the downfall of human wisdom. Both passages emphasize the consequences of ignoring God''s message, as seen in the loss of understanding among the wise.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 35, 1, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Works', 'Both passages emphasize a divine work that will occur in the listeners'' days, which they will not believe. The call to ''wonder'' and the warning against disbelief are central themes in both texts.', 'theme', 0.7549999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 60, 4, 17, 17, 'ye shall in no wise believe', 'Judgment and Unbelief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment beginning with those who have received the message, as seen in both passages. Acts 13:41 warns of disbelief leading to perishing, while 1 Peter 4:17 emphasizes judgment starting at the house of God.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 45, 11, 7, 14, 'work which ye shall in no wise believe', 'Spiritual Blindness and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness among Israel and the surprising work of God that leads to salvation for the Gentiles. Acts 13:41''s warning about disbelief resonates with Romans 11:7-8''s depiction of Israel being blinded, highlighting a shared concern about faith and recognition of God''s work.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 51, 1, 26, 27, 'work which ye shall in no wise believe', 'Mystery of Belief and Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a hidden work of God that is revealed to those who believe. Acts 13:41 warns of disbelief in God''s work, while Colossians 1:26-27 speaks of a mystery now made manifest to the saints.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 23, 28, 14, 22, 'ye despisers, and wonder, and perish', 'Judgment and Unbelief Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of scorn and disbelief. Acts 13:41 warns of perishing due to disbelief, paralleling Isaiah 28:14-22''s call to heed the Lord''s word against mockers. This connection highlights the theme of judgment for those who reject divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 20, 5, 12, 12, 'despisers', 'Despisers and Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of despising wisdom and instruction. Both passages address the consequences of rejecting guidance and the resulting peril.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 41, 40, 21, 41, 44, 'ye shall in no wise believe', 'Rejection and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection and its dire consequences. Both passages emphasize the idea of disbelief leading to destruction and the transfer of God''s favor to others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 42, 44, 28, 28, 28, 'the Gentiles besought that these words', 'Gentile Reception of Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of Gentiles seeking salvation. In both passages, the Gentiles express a desire to hear the message of God, emphasizing their openness to salvation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 42, 26, 3, 6, 6, 'these words might be preached to them', 'Gentiles Seeking God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of Gentiles desiring to hear God''s message. In Acts, the Gentiles ask to hear the words preached, paralleling Ezekiel''s mention of people who would listen if sent to them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 42, 40, 11, 21, 21, 'these words might be preached to them', 'Response to Preaching and Repentance', 'This connection highlights the response of the Gentiles in Acts seeking the message, paralleling the unrepentant cities in Matthew. Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing and responding to the message of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 42, 40, 19, 30, 30, NULL, 'First and Last Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusion, where the Gentiles, often seen as the last, seek the message of salvation. In Matthew, the reversal of status is emphasized, suggesting that those who are last will be prioritized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 42, 44, 10, 33, 33, 'that these words might be preached to them', 'Gentile Interest in God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the eagerness of Gentiles to hear God''s message. Both passages emphasize the desire of Gentiles to receive teachings about God, as seen in their requests to hear more.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 44, 11, 23, 23, 'grace of God', 'Connection of Grace and Exhortation', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of grace and encourage believers to remain steadfast in their faith. Acts 13:43 speaks of continuing in the grace of God, while Acts 11:23 highlights the joy of witnessing the grace of God and encourages cleaving to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 44, 14, 22, 22, 'continue in the grace of God', 'Encouragement to Continue in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of perseverance in faith. Both passages emphasize the importance of continuing in the grace of God and the faith amidst challenges.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 45, 3, 24, 24, 'continue in the grace of God', 'Connection of Grace and Justification', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of grace, with Acts 13:43 encouraging believers to continue in the grace of God, while Romans 3:24 speaks of being justified freely by his grace. This connection highlights the importance of grace in the process of salvation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 45, 5, 2, 2, 'continue in the grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of grace, with Acts highlighting the encouragement to continue in the grace of God, while Romans speaks of standing in grace through faith. This connection highlights the importance of grace in the believer''s life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 47, 5, 11, 11, 'persuaded them to continue', 'Persuasion in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of persuasion in ministry. In Acts, Paul and Barnabas persuade the followers to continue in grace, while in 2 Corinthians, Paul speaks of persuading men in light of the Lord''s terror.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 47, 6, 1, 1, 'grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of ''grace of God.'' Acts 13:43 encourages believers to continue in this grace, while 2 Corinthians 6:1 warns against receiving it in vain. This connection highlights the ongoing significance of grace in the believer''s life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 43, 48, 5, 1, 1, 'continue in the grace of God', 'Grace and Freedom Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of grace and liberty in the Christian faith. In Acts, Paul and Barnabas encourage believers to continue in the grace of God, while Galatians emphasizes standing firm in the freedom Christ provides.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 44, 1, 49, 10, 10, NULL, 'Gathering of the People', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people to hear God''s word. In Acts, the whole city comes together to hear the message, while Genesis speaks of the gathering of people to Shiloh, indicating a significant moment of unity and expectation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 44, 19, 110, 3, 3, 'the whole city together to hear', 'Willingness to Hear God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of people gathering to hear God''s message. Both passages emphasize a collective willingness and eagerness in the presence of divine power and holiness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 44, 23, 11, 10, 10, 'the whole city together to hear', 'Gathering of the Gentiles', 'This connection highlights the gathering of people to hear the word of God in Acts, paralleling the prophecy in Isaiah about the Gentiles seeking the root of Jesse. Both passages emphasize a significant moment of unity and interest from diverse groups in the message of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 44, 23, 60, 8, 8, 'whole city together to hear', 'Gathering to Hear the Word', 'This connection highlights the theme of people gathering to receive a message. In Acts, the whole city comes together to hear the word of God, while Isaiah speaks of people flying to their windows, suggesting a desire to receive something important.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 65, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Envy and Speaking Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of speaking against others out of envy or ignorance. Both passages emphasize the act of speaking evil, whether motivated by jealousy or a lack of understanding.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 44, 18, 6, 6, 'blaspheming', 'Opposition and Blasphemy Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition faced by Paul, with the Jews expressing envy and blasphemy in Acts 13:45 and Paul responding to similar blasphemy in Acts 18:6. This connection highlights the recurring theme of resistance to the message of the Gospel.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 44, 5, 17, 17, NULL, 'Indignation and Envy in Opposition', 'This connection highlights the emotional responses of the Jewish leaders in both passages. In Acts 13:45, the Jews are ''filled with envy,'' while in Acts 5:17, the high priest and his associates are ''filled with indignation,'' showcasing a common theme of opposition to the apostles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 52, 2, 16, 16, 'filled with envy', 'Envy and Opposition to Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the opposition faced by Paul and the early Christians from the Jews. Acts 13:45 highlights the Jews'' envy and blasphemy against Paul''s message, while 1 Thessalonians 2:16 speaks of their efforts to prevent Gentiles from being saved.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 40, 27, 18, 18, 'filled with envy', 'Envy Leading to Conflict', 'Both passages emphasize the role of envy in provoking actions against others. In Acts, the Jews'' envy leads them to contradict Paul, while in Matthew, envy motivates the delivery of Jesus to be crucified.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 46, 3, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Envy and Strife', 'This connection highlights the theme of envy present in both passages. Acts 13:45 describes the Jews'' envy leading to strife against Paul, while 1 Corinthians 3:3 addresses the resulting divisions and strife among believers due to envy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 45, 60, 4, 4, 4, NULL, 'Envy and Speaking Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of envy leading to speaking evil. In both passages, individuals react negatively to others'' actions, expressing their discontent through blasphemy or speaking evil.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 44, 28, 28, 28, 'we turn to the Gentiles', 'Salvation for the Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the outreach to the Gentiles after the rejection by the Jews. Paul and Barnabas declare their intention to turn to the Gentiles, while the later passage confirms that the salvation of God is sent to them.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 40, 21, 43, 43, 'judge yourselves unworthy of everlasting life', 'Rejection and New Recipients', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of the original audience and the subsequent offer of God''s message to others. Acts 13:46 speaks of turning to the Gentiles after the Jews judged themselves unworthy, paralleling Matthew 21:43''s declaration of the kingdom being given to a different nation.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 44, 18, 5, 6, 'judge yourselves unworthy of everlasting life', 'Paul''s Ministry to the Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s decision to turn to the Gentiles after facing opposition from the Jews. In each instance, he declares that the Jews have judged themselves unworthy of everlasting life, leading him to focus on the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 45, 2, 10, 10, NULL, 'Order of Gospel Proclamation', 'Both passages emphasize the priority of the Jews in receiving the word of God. Acts 13:46 highlights the necessity of speaking to the Jews first, while Romans 2:10 states that glory is given to the Jew first, indicating a consistent theme of the Jewish priority in the gospel message.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 45, 1, 16, 16, NULL, 'Gospel''s Priority to the Jew', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of the gospel being presented to the Jews first. Acts 13:46 highlights the rejection by the Jews, while Romans 1:16 affirms the order of the gospel''s proclamation, indicating its importance to the Jews before reaching the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 43, 1, 11, 11, NULL, 'Rejection of God''s Message', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of God''s word by His own people. In Acts, Paul and Barnabas note that the Jews judged themselves unworthy, while John highlights that Jesus came to His own but was not received.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 46, 23, 55, 5, 5, 'turn to the Gentiles', 'Connection of Gentile Inclusion', 'Both passages emphasize the outreach to nations that are not initially aware of God. Acts 13:46 highlights the turning to the Gentiles, while Isaiah 55:5 speaks of nations running to God. This connection highlights the theme of God''s message extending beyond Israel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 13, 47, 23, 49, 6, 6, 'a light of the Gentiles', 'Connection of Light and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize being a light to the Gentiles and bringing salvation to the ends of the earth. This connection highlights the role of the servant in reaching beyond Israel to all nations.', 'theme', 0.538, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
